<div id="review_911009435" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/911009435" />
    <a title="Fabian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1036893-fabian"><img alt="Fabian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514061293p2/1036893.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/911009435?book_show_action=true">Apr 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fabian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fabian" href="/user/show/1036893-fabian">Fabian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer911009435" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8002265065891379249">A delight (&amp; the first of Gaiman&apos;s books that I&apos;ve read to get the full ***** from me)! It&apos;s got that outrageous &quot;Freaky Friday&quot;/Prince &amp; the Pauper narrative; Britishisms a-la Evelyn Waugh; and a peck of Douglas Adams&apos;s brand of whimsy (this is infinitely better than Hitchhiker&apos;s Guide, &amp; much better than the author&apos;s own Stardust AND Neverwhere). It&apos;s adorably Beetlejuician! What&apos;s not to like, huh?</span>
  <span id="freeText8002265065891379249" style="display:none">A delight (&amp; the first of Gaiman's books that I've read to get the full ***** from me)! It's got that outrageous "Freaky Friday"/Prince &amp; the Pauper narrative; Britishisms a-la Evelyn Waugh; and a peck of Douglas Adams's brand of whimsy (this is infinitely better than Hitchhiker's Guide, &amp; much better than the author's own Stardust AND Neverwhere). It's adorably Beetlejuician! What's not to like, huh?</span>
