        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer144105467" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1473317112249982138">Mr. Gaiman has the same problem as Terry Pratchet. He can present the material, but he can&apos;t make me care. It&apos;s not a good sign when you&apos;re halfway through a book and you realize that if you put down the book and walked away right then and there, and never found out how the book ended, you wouldn&apos;t care. I don&apos;t care whether things work out between him and Rosie. I don&apos;t care if his dad is still alive or not. I don&apos;t care if he and his brother ever make up. I wouldn&apos;t care if the author ended th</span>
  <span id="freeText1473317112249982138" style="display:none">Mr. Gaiman has the same problem as Terry Pratchet. He can present the material, but he can't make me care. It's not a good sign when you're halfway through a book and you realize that if you put down the book and walked away right then and there, and never found out how the book ended, you wouldn't care. I don't care whether things work out between him and Rosie. I don't care if his dad is still alive or not. I don't care if he and his brother ever make up. I wouldn't care if the author ended the book with 'then a bomb exploded and they all died the end'. I am unable to get interested in any of the characters or the plot. And the book was supposed to be funny, but most of the jokes just made it seem like he was trying way too hard. I've had this problem with all of Gaiman's books. I guess it just not my thing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1473317112249982138" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

